comment_data.body:
Bellow is how I used to use `on_new_config` with `nvim-lspconfig` before I switched to `vim.lsp`. I used it for changing to the closest `.venv` to a python file with `pyright`. I have a project that has submodules and each submodule needs its own set of packages and python versions. Maybe this is not an example for why we need `on_new_config` but it did take me a minute to figure out why my setup was not working and how to change it.

```
on_new_config = function(client, dir)

    -- Set python path to the first python executable found in the current directory or its parents
    vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd({ "BufEnter" }, {
      -- group = lsp_buffer_group,
      buffer = vim.api.nvim_get_current_buf(),
      callback = function()
        local venv = vim.fs.root(dir, { '.venv', '.envrc', 'requirements.txt', 'pyproject.toml', 'ruff.toml', '.ruff.toml', '.git' })
        local hits = vim.fs.find( { 'python' }, { limit = math.huge, path = venv } )
        local result = vim.iter(hits)
          :fold({ min_length = nil, min_str = nil },
          function(acc, str)
            if acc.min_length == nil or #str < acc.min_length then
              acc.min_length = #str
              acc.min_str = str
            end
            return acc
          end)

        if result.min_str == nil then
          vim.notify( 'Could not find python path for ' .. dir, vim.log.levels.WARN )
          return
        end

        client.settings.python = vim.tbl_deep_extend('force', client.settings.python, { pythonPath = result.min_str } )
      end,
    })
  end,
```

I stopped using `nvim-lspconfig` in favor of `vim.lsp` and now I can do the same with `on_attach`. Full example bellow:

```
{
  single_file_support = true,

  filetypes = {"python"},
  cmd = {"pyright-langserver", "--stdio"},

  root_markers = {".venv", "requirements.txt", "pyproject.toml", "ruff.toml", ".ruff.toml", ".git"},

  settings = {
    pyright = {
      disableOrganizeImports = true, -- Ruff"s
    },
    python = {
      analysis = {
        ignore = {"*"}, -- Ruff"s
        autoSearchPaths = true,
        diagnosticMode = "openFilesOnly",
        useLibraryCodeForTypes = true,
      }
    }
  },

  on_attach = function(client, bufnr)
    local function update_python_path()
      local dir = vim.fn.expand("%:p:h")
      local root = vim.fs.find(
        { ".venv", ".envrc", "requirements.txt", "pyproject.toml", "ruff.toml", ".ruff.toml", ".git" },
        { path = dir, upward = true, stop = vim.fn.expand("~"), limit = 1 }
      )[1]

      local hit = vim.fs.find(
        { "python" },
        { path = root, upward = false, type = "link", ignore = function(_, _) return false end, limit = 1 }
      )[1]
      or vim.fn.trim(vim.fn.system("which python"))

      client.config.settings.python = vim.tbl_deep_extend("force", client.config.settings.python, { pythonPath = hit })

      client.notify("workspace/didChangeConfiguration", { settings = { python = client.config.settings.python } })
    end

    vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd("BufEnter", { buffer = bufnr, callback = update_python_path })
    update_python_path()
  end,
}

```

Interestingly, the first version that is based on `nvim-lspconfig` and `on_new_config` would append the newly found `.venv` as a workspace to the same pyright whereas the `vim.lsp` and `on_attach` spawns a new pyright for each `.venv`.

My use of `on_new_config` is primarily to change which lua version the lsp should be using for different projects. I work on a project using Lua 5.4 and use nvim which is LuaJIT. I also load `.luacheckrc` to apply its settings to the lsp. I don't see how to do that with the options given above.

`fun(config: vim.lsp.Config, callback: fun(config: vim.lsp.Config))` would let you dynamically alter the config, but how do you know what code/project you're targeting? And would the config returned by that function be specific to that lsp or clobber settings for other lsp instances.

The `LspAttach` fires after the lsp starts, so isn't it too late to configure it?

I have [extracted a long version](https://gist.github.com/idbrii/6e4d7addcc391992fafb38d7a80adacc) of my setup (was using something close to that on nvim-lspconfig@v0.1.8), but here's a brief version:

```lua
require 'lspconfig'.lua_ls.setup {
  on_new_config = function(cfg, new_root_dir)
    if new_root_dir:find("%pvim") then
      cfg.settings.Lua = {
        runtime = {
          version = 'LuaJIT',
        },
        workspace = {
          checkThirdParty = false,
          library = {
            vim.env.VIMRUNTIME,  -- Make the server aware of Neovim runtime files
          },
        },
        diagnostics = {
          globals = {
            'vim',
          }
        },
      }
    else
      cfg.settings.Lua = {
        runtime = {
          version = 'Lua5.4',
        },
        workspace = {
          checkThirdParty = false,
          maxPreload = 100000,
          ignoreDir = {".git", ".svn", ".vs"}
        },
      }
    end
  end,
  settings = {
    Lua = {}
  },
}
```
